---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Eight names, two chambers · Riksdag Revealed"
  description="The 2018-22 and 2022-26 Riksdag mandates read against each other. The same eight parties produced two structurally different chambers. The parties stayed mostly the same; the bloc structure changed completely."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Riksdag Revealed · Two mandates, 2018-2026</p>
      <h1>Eight names, two chambers</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Sweden goes to the polls in September 2026 with the same eight
        parties that were on the 2018 ballot. The Riksdag those parties
        operated in over the last four years bears little structural
        resemblance to the one they operated in over the four years
        before that. The parties stayed mostly the same. The chamber
        did not.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      This article reads the 2018-22 mandate against the 2022-26
      mandate, using the same measurements on both. It is intended as
      the entry point to a longer analysis that has mandate-specific
      deep-dives at <a href={`${base}/2018-2022`}>/2018-2022</a> and
      <a href={`${base}/2022-2026`}>/2022-2026</a>. The shared question
      across the two pieces is what stayed the same and what changed
      between 2018 and 2026, and what that means for a voter looking
      at the September 2026 ballot.
    </p>

    <p>
      The central claim of this article can be stated in one sentence.
      Between 2018 and 2026 the parties on the Swedish ballot have
      drifted in manifesto register but remain recognisable as the
      same parties; the bloc structure they operate in has been
      restructured. The implication for a 2026 voter is that the
      ballot looks familiar, but the chamber that the ballot fills is
      organised differently than it was when the previous mandate
      began.
    </p>

    <h2>Two chambers, side by side</h2>

    <p>
      Every chamber vote of each mandate, member by member, projected
      into two dimensions through PCA on the year's vote matrix. The
      two figures use the same projection method on the same eight
      parties; each is fitted independently on its own mandate's votes.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/54_per_mandate_centroid_maps.png`} alt="Side-by-side PC1 vs PC2 chamber maps for 2018-22 and 2022-26" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Left: 2018-22. Right: 2022-26. Each dot is a Member of
        Parliament; the labelled circles are party centroids.
        Sverigedemokraterna sits on its own arm in 2018-22, far from
        every other party on PC2. In 2022-26 Sverigedemokraterna has
        joined the Tidö cluster on the right of PC1 alongside M, KD
        and L.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      In 2018-22 the chamber organises into roughly three clusters: a
      red-green grouping of S, V and MP on one side of PC1, an
      Alliance grouping of M and KD on the other, with C and L between
      them, and Sverigedemokraterna far from everything else on PC2.
      The Tidö parties as a four-party group do not appear; M, KD, L
      and SD are in four different regions of the map.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 2022-26 the picture is restructured. M, KD, L and SD now sit
      together on the right of PC1, separated from S on the upper
      left, with V and MP at the bottom of PC2 and C in between. The
      Tidö bloc that the previous mandate did not contain is now
      present as a single tight cluster. This is not a relabelling.
      The parties on each side did not change names. The way the
      chamber arranges itself in vote space did.
    </p>

    <h2>The Tidö bloc is a formation, not a fact of nature</h2>

    <p>
      The starkest single way to see this is to count how often the
      four Tidö parties voted the same way in chamber votes per
      parliamentary year, across both mandates.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/51_tido_agreement_longitudinal.png`} alt="Share of chamber votes per riksmöte where M, KD, L and SD voted unanimously" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Share of contested chamber votes per riksmöte where M, KD, L
        and SD all voted the same way. In the previous mandate the
        four parties voted together on 16 to 30 percent of contested
        votes. The share jumped to 67 percent at the start of 2022-23
        and rose to 98 percent by the election year of 2025-26.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The figure tells the story directly. The four parties of Tidö
      did not vote together before 2022. They went from voting
      together less than a third of the time to voting together
      almost unanimously over four years. The transition is sharp
      and dated: it began at the start of the 2022-26 mandate, not
      gradually before it, and accelerated through the mandate.
    </p>

    <p>
      The bloc is therefore not a re-discovery of latent affinities
      between the four parties. It is a coalition formation that
      took place during a particular mandate and reshaped how the
      same four parties' MPs behave on the floor.
    </p>

    <h2>The L caucus's drift toward KD and M is mandate-specific</h2>

    <p>
      The main 2022-26 article identified a striking pattern: eight
      of the twelve Members of Parliament with the highest defection
      ratio were Liberalerna MPs whose voting record sat closer to
      KD or M than to L. The L caucus, by that measurement, behaved
      like a caucus inside the Christian-Democratic and Moderate
      voting clusters rather than its own. The longitudinal question
      is whether the L-defectors pattern existed before Tidö or
      emerged with it.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/52_defectors_comparison.png`} alt="Top 12 behavioural defectors per mandate, side by side" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        For each mandate, the 12 Members of Parliament with the
        highest distance-to-own-party-centroid relative to
        distance-to-nearest-other-party. Each label gives the MP's
        own party and the nearest-other-party in parentheses.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The two lists are different in composition. The 2018-22 list
      is dominated by Vänsterpartiet members (Gudrun Nordborg, Jonas
      Sjöstedt, Hillevi Larsson and others) and a number of
      Socialdemokrat MPs whose voting records sit closer to
      Miljöpartiet than to S. Liberalerna does not appear prominently;
      the one C-defector (Abir Al-Sahlani) and one S-MP-defector
      (Kadir Kasirga) are the only non-V cases in the top eight.
    </p>

    <p>
      The 2022-26 list is dominated by Liberalerna MPs (Gulan Avci,
      Lina Nordquist, Malin Danielsson, Martin Melin, Fredrik Malm,
      Mauricio Rojas, Jakob Olofsgård, Helena Gellerman) whose voting
      records sit substantially closer to Kristdemokraterna or
      Moderaterna than to Liberalerna. Margareta Cederfelt (M) sits
      closer to L; Kjell-Arne Ottosson (KD) sits closer to M.
    </p>

    <p>
      The L-defectors phenomenon is therefore not a long-running
      drift of the L caucus that finally became measurable. It is a
      property of the 2022-26 mandate specifically, and it appeared
      at the same time as the Tidö formation. A voter who reads the
      L name on the 2026 ballot and assumes its members vote like the
      2018-22 L caucus would be using an out-of-date model.
    </p>

    <h2>What stayed the same: parties as manifestos</h2>

    <p>
      Election manifestos are documents the parties write ahead of
      each election. They are stable election-level objects, and the
      register of each manifesto is a reasonable way to ask whether
      the party that put it forward is recognisable as the same party
      across cycles. Using the same keyword classifier the main
      article used for 2022, we re-classified the eight 2018
      manifestos along the same three dimensions: diagnosis (what is
      wrong with Sweden), end-state (what should it be), and
      mechanism (how to get there).
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/50_manifesto_element_trajectories.png`} alt="Per-party register share across 2018 and 2022 manifestos" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party share of substantive sentences classified into each
        register, across 2018, 2022 and 2026 (the L 2026 valmanifest
        is included where available). Lines connect the same party
        across years.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two parties are remarkably stable across the cycle. Vänsterpartiet
      and Liberalerna sit at essentially the same register shares in
      2022 as in 2018, with all three element shares within 1 to 2
      percentage points across years. L's 2026 manifesto continues
      that pattern. These parties produce documents that look like
      themselves cycle after cycle.
    </p>

    <p>
      Four parties show meaningful register drift between 2018 and
      2022. Sverigedemokraterna's diagnosis share rose from 5.7
      percent to 12.8 percent, doubling the share of sentences that
      describe what is wrong with Sweden. Kristdemokraterna's
      diagnosis share rose from 3.9 percent to 10.9 percent and its
      end-state share fell from 9.9 percent to 3.1 percent;
      Kristdemokraterna's 2022 manifesto is essentially a critique
      document with very little aspirational language.
      Moderaterna's mechanism share rose from 8.2 percent to 20.5
      percent, tripling the proportion of policy-instrument language.
      Centerpartiet's diagnosis share fell from 9.6 to 4.7 percent;
      the party became the most forward-looking of the eight by the
      time of the 2022 manifesto.
    </p>

    <p>
      The drift is real and large enough to take seriously, but it
      does not produce eight different parties. Each one is
      recognisable as the same party in 2022 as it was in 2018; what
      changes is the proportion of its content devoted to diagnosis
      versus end-state versus mechanism. The signature value
      vocabularies (frihet for L, klimat for MP, trygghet for KD,
      jämlikhet for V, ordning for M, jämställdhet for C, nationell
      identitet for SD, kollektivets for S) survive across the cycle.
    </p>

    <h2>Reservations as the transition signal</h2>

    <p>
      Reservations are dissenting opinions filed by opposition
      parties on committee reports. They are the principal way an
      opposition party puts its alternative reasoning on the
      parliamentary record. Cabinet parties write very few
      reservations because they are part of the majority. The count
      of reservations filed per party per riksmöte is therefore a
      direct indicator of whether the party was in opposition or in
      government during that year.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/57_reservations_longitudinal.png`} alt="Reservations filed per party per riksmöte across both mandates" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Reservations filed per party and parliamentary year across
        both mandates. Sverigedemokraterna is highlighted. The
        cabinet party transition is visible: M, KD and L drop from
        several hundred reservations per year in 2018-22 to a
        single-digit count throughout 2022-26.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Several patterns are visible in the same figure. M, KD and L's
      reservations fell from a few hundred per year in 2018-22 (a
      normal opposition pattern) to single-digit counts throughout
      2022-26 (a normal cabinet pattern). C, V, MP and S filed
      hundreds of reservations per year throughout both mandates,
      consistent with their opposition or quasi-opposition role in
      both periods.
    </p>

    <p>
      Sverigedemokraterna's trajectory does not fit either pattern.
      In 2018-22 SD filed between 697 and 1,093 reservations per
      year (heavy opposition activity), the highest count of any
      party. In 2022-26 the count began at 749 and ended at 17. The
      17-reservation total for 2025-26 is the lowest by any party
      across the entire eight-year window other than the cabinet
      parties M, KD and L. Sverigedemokraterna stopped behaving like
      an opposition party on the reservation record one year before
      the 2026 election, even though it does not formally hold a
      cabinet seat.
    </p>

    <h2>Vote-versus-reasoning, two mandates</h2>

    <p>
      Voting together is not the same as reasoning together. For
      every party pair in each mandate we measured a vote-stance
      similarity from the chamber record and a topic-centred cosine
      reasoning similarity from the parties' reservation reasoning
      vectors (with speech-based vectors as fallback for cabinet
      cells). The two metrics are correlated but the residuals are
      where the most informative pairs sit.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/58_vote_vs_reasoning_18_22.png`} alt="Vote-versus-reasoning scatter for 2018-22" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        2018-22 mandate. Each point is one party pair. The dashed
        line is the cross-pair trend. Highlighted pairs: S-MP
        (Löfven cabinet partners, vote and reason alike); KD-M
        (Alliance partners, vote and reason alike); M-SD (vote alike
        and reasoning at moderate similarity).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/34_vote_vs_reasoning.png`} alt="Vote-versus-reasoning scatter for 2022-26" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        2022-26 mandate, using unified topic IDs and speech-based
        fallback for cabinet cells. Highlighted: V-MP (vote and
        reason alike, the only above-trend opposition pair); S-C
        (vote alike, argue apart); M-SD, L-SD, KD-SD (vote alike,
        argue apart).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      In 2018-22 the named bloc pairs sit above the cross-pair trend
      line: S-MP (the Löfven cabinet partners), KD-M (Alliance
      partners), M-SD (the early stages of vote convergence with
      moderate reasoning similarity). The chamber's bloc structure
      is visible in the pair pattern, and the pairs that vote alike
      generally also argue alike.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 2022-26 the picture changes substantively. V-MP is the only
      above-trend pair, indicating a genuine reasoning convergence
      to match the vote convergence. The three Tidö-SD pairs
      (M-SD, L-SD, KD-SD) sit well below the trend line: vote
      similarity is around 0.84 but reasoning similarity is
      negative. Sverigedemokraterna votes with the cabinet parties
      but writes in a parliamentary register that is much closer to
      the opposition parties than to the cabinet's. The same applies
      in the other direction: M, KD and L vote with SD but reason
      apart from it.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is a substantive change from the picture in the published
      single-mandate version of the 2022-26 article, which
      characterised M-SD as "vote alike and argue alike". Under the
      unified topic structure used here, with the speech-based
      fallback for the cabinet cells that do not have reservation
      coverage, the M-SD pair sits below the cross-pair trend. The
      Tidö parties vote as a bloc; their parliamentary reasoning
      languages are not as aligned as their votes.
    </p>

    <h2>Pair correlations: the L snap</h2>

    <p>
      The cleanest single way to see the mandate boundary is to
      trace selected party pairs' vote correlation through the eight
      parliamentary years. The metric is Pearson correlation of
      per-event mean vote vectors, computed per riksmöte.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/55_pair_vote_correlation_longitudinal.png`} alt="Per-year pair vote correlation across both mandates" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Selected party pairs' vote correlation per riksmöte across
        both mandates. Higher values mean the two parties voted more
        similarly on average that year.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two lines tell the central story. L-M correlation sat at 0.04
      to 0.14 across all four years of 2018-22. From the first year
      of 2022-26 it jumped to 0.996. L-KD followed the same path
      (0.05 to 0.18 in 2018-22, 0.81 to 0.99 in 2022-26). The L
      caucus's voting behaviour snapped into the Moderate and
      Christian Democratic register at the mandate boundary. There
      was no gradual drift; the chamber-level alignment changed
      essentially overnight.
    </p>

    <p>
      M-SD has a different shape. In 2018-22 the M-SD correlation
      rose gradually from -0.10 to 0.20 as the political distance
      between the parties shrank. In early 2022-26 the correlation
      drops back toward 0, then jumps to 0.31 in 2025-26. Vote
      correlation as a metric is sensitive to which party's positions
      have the most variance in a given year; the Tidö-bloc
      unanimity figure above is the cleaner read on the M-SD
      relationship inside this mandate.
    </p>

    <h2>For a 2026 voter</h2>

    <p>
      The 2026 ballot lists the same eight parties as the 2018
      ballot. A voter looking at those names is using a familiar
      menu. The chamber that menu fills is not the chamber the
      same parties operated in four years ago.
    </p>

    <p>
      Three things follow from this for an informed vote.
    </p>

    <p>
      First, the four parties of the Tidö bloc (M, KD, L and SD) do
      not function as four distinct options on the parliamentary
      record of this mandate. Their per-year vote correlations are
      at or near 1.0; their unanimity on contested votes was 98
      percent in the election year. A voter who weights one of the
      four parties against another using their 2018-22 patterns is
      using a model that does not apply to 2022-26.
    </p>

    <p>
      Second, the L caucus's floor-vote behaviour does not match the
      L manifesto, the L committee work, or the L caucus's 2018-22
      pattern. The 2026 L valmanifest "För din frihet" reasserts a
      classical-liberal value vocabulary, but the L MPs' votes
      across the previous four years cluster with KD and M. The
      gap between manifesto and floor-vote is wider for L than for
      any other party.
    </p>

    <p>
      Third, the parties whose identity has stayed most recognisable
      across the cycle (V on the left, L in the centre on a
      manifesto basis) are not necessarily the parties whose
      chamber-record behaviour has stayed most recognisable. V is
      stable in both layers; L is stable on the manifesto but not on
      the floor vote. The two layers can move independently, and a
      voter who reads only one layer (manifesto or chamber record)
      will miss the other.
    </p>

    <h3>Where the deep-dives live</h3>

    <p>
      Each mandate has a dedicated page that uses the same eight
      parties, the same topic clustering, and the same SBERT
      embedding pipeline. The 2018-22 deep-dive is at
      <a href={`${base}/2018-2022`}>/2018-2022</a> and the 2022-26
      deep-dive at <a href={`${base}/2022-2026`}>/2022-2026</a>. The
      2022-26 page also contains a companion analysis of L's 2026
      valmanifest, the first finalised 2026 election document in the
      corpus.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      All analysis is based on reproducible methods over public data
      from <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>
      (votes, reservations, speeches) and the SND "Vi vill" archive
      (election manifestos 2018, 2022). The topic clustering used
      throughout is a 28-cluster KMeans on the union of decision
      points from both mandates, with the K decision documented in
      the method page. Source code at
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .method-note {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: var(--ink-muted, #555);
  }
</style>
